                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Dec. 17: The Centre today conceded for the first time that it was against the Salwa Judum civil militia campaign in Chhattisgarh.           ion home minister P. Chidambaram made Delhis stand clear when, in response to a question, he told the Rajya Sabha that the state-backed, anti-Maoist campaign was an organisation the Centre had nothing to do with.          
	We are not in favour of non-state actors taking law enforcement in their hands, Chidambaram said, asked if the Centre would advise the state government to dismantle the militia.The campaign, launched in 2005 in Naxalite-infested Chhattisgarh, has been under fire for alleged human rights violations. Negative comments have also come from the Supreme Court and the Planning Commission.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Pakistan high commissioner Shahid Malik on Wednesday said Jaish-e-Mohammed chief Masood Azhar was not under house arrest and his whereabouts were not known. We are looking for him. He is not under house arrest, Malik said, contradicting Pakistan defence minister Chaudhary Mukhtar Ahmads claim.                  
	 London (PTI): A UK court has sentenced to life imprisonment an Indian who sexually assaulted and killed a fellow student from Andhra Pradesh. Nagaraja Kumar Nalluri had been accused of killing Samrajya Jyothirmai Vempala by hitting her on the head.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Asok Kumar Ganguly, R.M. Lodha and H.L. Dattu were today sworn in as judges of the Supreme Court, with the apex court collegium having its way over the Centres reservations. The Centre had asked to take into consideration the seniority of chief justices of three other high courts.                   
	 New Delhi: A 12-year-old labrador suffering from osteoarthritis has been allowed to use the lift of a building after its owner won a case against the housing society, which did not allow Ajay Marathe to take his pet in the lift. Marathe, 52, who lived on the fifth floor said it was difficult for him to carry the 35kg dog for its walks.                                                                                                                         
